We already exhibit less empathy and understanding for each other than we are capable of, and digital boundaries absolutely make that worse. There are complex consequences to every decision, and we have to really consider the *unintended* consequences of demanding permanent WFH.

But that doesn’t mean permanent WFH is the grand solution. The physical office isn’t the real cause of those problems. They have other, deeper root causes that we should absolutely fight to fix. If we don’t, they’ll keep festering whether we’re at home or not.

Long commutes are stupid. Working long, grueling hours sucks. Missing out on important family time or fighting for time to take care of yourself or loved ones is ridiculous. WFH full-time temporarily relieved a lot of those issues and made us see the value of our sacrifices.

Rather than accepting as a given that we hate our bosses and coworkers, and will gladly isolate ourselves from them as much as possible, shouldn’t we just expect more of them? Should we be better bosses and coworkers to each other? What if we were more empathetic and forgiving?

“But,” many of them they say, “I don’t need to get along with my coworkers. I don’t even like them now, so who cares if I don’t get along with them in the future?” Well, never being in the same room with them certainly won’t help, but also, why are we ok with that?

Remember Zoom fatigue? Our animal brains don’t process computer-humans the same way we process real humans. We all know the best communication is face-to-face. Have you ever tried to work out a complicated disagreement over phone or text, and then finally resolved it in person?

I hear some people saying they “never” really need to go to an office, and like companies who resist any WFH at all, they are being unrealistic. They envision a completely virtual work life where coworkers are digital sounds, images, and text only. That’s really not wise.

If possible, people need to be able to WFH. I spent years fighting for my employees to be able to WFH at a company that just did not trust its employees. They reluctantly allow WFH now because their distrust was proven unfounded. But we have to be careful about overcorrection. 🧵
